102 §29-2B-5
103 For purposes of this chapter, the following terms have
104 the following meanings:
105 (1) AGENCY. Any department, board, commission, office,
106 institution, or other unit of state government that receives
107 appropriations from the state.
108 (2) CAUSAL IMPACT EVALUATION. A rigorous evaluation
109 that uses experimental or quasi-experimental methods to
110 determine whether a program caused observed outcomes,
111 isolating the program's effects from other factors.
112 (3) EVALUATION PLAN. A written document that describes
Page 4

(3) EVALUATION PLAN. A written document that describes
SB317 INTRODUCED
113 how an agency will assess a program's implementation, outputs,
114 and outcomes, including the data sources, indicators, and
115 methods to be used.
116 (4) LOGIC MODEL. A visual or narrative representation
117 that shows the logical relationships between a program's
118 resources, activities, outputs, and intended outcomes.
119 (5) MAJOR EXPANSION. An increase in a program's
120 appropriation of 25 percent or more compared to the prior
121 fiscal year, or an expansion that significantly changes the
122 program's target population, service delivery method, or
123 geographic scope.
124 (6) NEW PROGRAM. A program that receives an
125 appropriation for the first time and that is not a
126 continuation or modification of an existing program under a
127 different name or organizational structure.
128 (7) PRELIMINARY STUDY. An evaluation or examination of
129 a proposed or existing policy or program conducted before or
130 during legislative consideration, designed to inform
131 legislative decisions about program design, feasibility, or
132 resource requirements.
133 (8) PRIORITY EVALUATION QUESTION. A significant
134 question about a program's implementation, effectiveness, or
135 outcomes that an agency or the commission identifies as
136 warranting systematic evaluation.
137 §29-2B-6
138 The Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of Services
139 shall develop and publish on its website the evaluation
140 standards used in the performance of evaluations of services.
Page 5

standards used in the performance of evaluations of services.
SB317 INTRODUCED
141 §29-2B-7
142 (a) Each year, within 30 days of the conclusion of the
143 regular session of the Legislature, or any special session
144 where an appropriations act is enacted, the Legislative
145 Services Agency shall identify each new program or major
146 expansion of an existing program for which an agency received
147 an appropriation and notify the agency and the Alabama
148 Commission on the Evaluation of Services of the programs
149 subject to the provisions of this chapter.
150 (b) Each agency shall prepare an evaluation plan for
151 each new program and each major expansion of an existing
152 program that is enacted in an appropriations act, as follows:
153 (1) The evaluation plan shall, at a minimum, describe
154 the program's objectives, target population, key activities,
155 expected inputs, outputs, intended outcomes, and benchmarks
156 for intended outcomes. These variables shall be incorporated
157 into a logic model in the plan.
158 (2) The evaluation plan shall identify the indicators
159 the agency will use to track inputs, outputs, and key
160 outcomes; and for each, describe the data sources and explain
161 how the measures will be calculated for each indicator.
162 (3) The evaluation plan shall classify the planned
163 level of evaluation (for example, monitoring, outcome
164 evaluation, or causal impact evaluation) consistent with the
165 typology in the standards issued under Section 29-2B-6.
166 (4) For programs meeting criteria established in
167 guidance under Section 29-2B-6, the evaluation plan shall
168 include a proposal for a causal impact evaluation or a
Page 6

include a proposal for a causal impact evaluation or a
SB317 INTRODUCED
169 justification for why such an evaluation is not feasible or
170 appropriate.
171 (5) Evaluation plans shall be submitted to the Alabama
172 Commission on the Evaluation of Services for approval and
173 publication on its website, per the standards and guidance
174 issued under Section 29-2B-6, before data is analyzed.
175 §29-2B-8
176 (a) For each program subject to this chapter, the
177 agency shall prepare and submit evaluation reports to the
178 Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of Services on a schedule
179 specified in the standards issued under Section 29-2B-6, which
180 shall include at a minimum:
181 (1) A description of the program as implemented,
182 including any material deviations from the original evaluation
183 plan;
184 (2) Results on the agreed-upon input, output, and
185 outcome indicators, including baseline values and trends over
186 time;
187 (3) For programs with a causal impact evaluation, a
188 summary of the evaluation design, key findings, and
189 limitations; and
190 (4) The agency's interpretation of the findings and
191 planned actions in response (for example, continuation,
192 expansion, modification, or termination).
193 (b) The Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of
194 Services shall publish submitted evaluation reports on its
195 website.
196 §29-2B-9
Page 7

§29-2B-9
SB317 INTRODUCED
197 The Legislature, by language in an appropriations act
198 or other act, may require an evaluation of a specific program
199 or line item. Such a provision may:
200 (1) Specify that no more than a stated percentage of
201 funds may be expended until the agency has submitted an
202 evaluation plan meeting the standards of this chapter;
203 (2) Require that an evaluation report be submitted by a
204 certain date and that continuation, renewal, or expansion of
205 funding in a subsequent fiscal year shall consider the
206 findings; or
207 (3) Identify any additional or different indicators or
208 evaluation questions that are particularly important for the
209 program in question.
210 §29-2B-10
211 (a) The Legislature, by request of the Joint
212 Legislative Committee on Finances and Budget or by language in
213 an appropriations act or other act, may direct the Alabama
214 Commission on the Evaluation of Services to conduct a
215 preliminary study of proposed or existing policies or
216 programs.
217 (b) Any action directing a preliminary study shall
218 specify:
219 (1) The policy or program to be examined; and
220 (2) The questions or issues the study should address.
221 (c) The Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of
222 Services shall coordinate with the respective agencies or
223 entities impacted by the study to:
224 (1) Confirm the scope and objectives of the study;
Page 8

(1) Confirm the scope and objectives of the study;
SB317 INTRODUCED
225 (2) Establish a timeline for completion based on study
226 complexity and available resources;
227 (3) Identify necessary resources, including estimated
228 costs and staffing needs; and
229 (4) Determine the content and format of the final
230 report.
231 (d) If the Alabama Commission on the Evaluation of
232 Services determines that completing a preliminary study as
233 specified would require resources or time periods that exceed
234 available capacity of the commission or agency, the commission
235 may propose to the Legislature modifications to the study
236 scope, timeline, or resource allocation.
237 (e) Preliminary studies may examine:
238 (1) The feasibility of proposed programs or policies;
239 (2) Estimated costs and potential fiscal impacts;
240 (3) Experiences with similar programs in other
241 jurisdictions;
242 (4) Available data and evidence related to the policy
243 area;
244 (5) Evaluation design options if the policy or program
245 is enacted; or
246 (6) Expected implementation challenges and resource
247 requirements.
248 (f) Each preliminary study report shall include:
249 (1) A description of the policy or program examined;
250 (2) The study methodology and data sources used;
251 (3) Key findings addressing the questions specified in
252 the directing act;
